Step 1: Wiring the LDR (Ambient Light Monitor)
	Place the LDR on a breadboard. Connect one terminal to the 3.3V pin of the ESP32.
	Connect the second terminal to an analog input pin (e.g., GPIO 4 / ADC1).
	Connect a 10"k" Ω pull-down resistor from that same analog pin terminal to the GND pin. This creates a voltage divider network to translate light resistance variations into readable analog voltages.
Step 2: Wiring the PIR Sensor (Occupancy Core)
	Connect the VCC pin of the PIR sensor to the 5V / VIN pin of the micro-controller board.
	Connect the GND pin of the PIR sensor to the common GND rail on your layout.
	Connect the middle OUT digital pin of the PIR to GPIO 19.
Step 3: Wiring the PWM Controller & Output Array
Safety Warning: Do not connect high-draw LED arrays directly to microcontroller GPIO pins to prevent thermal damage. Always route power through a logic-level switching MOSFET.
	Connect GPIO 18 (designated as your PWM output) to the Gate (G) pin of the IRF540N MOSFET module.
	Connect the Source (S) pin of the MOSFET directly to the common GND rail.
	Connect the negative terminal (-) of your 12V LED Strip to the Drain (D) pin of the MOSFET.
	Connect the positive terminal (+) of your 12V LED Strip directly to the positive terminal of the 12V External Power Supply.
	Connect the negative ground terminal of the 12V external power supply directly to the micro-controller's GND pin to establish a unified reference ground.
Step 4: Logic Configuration & Testing Loop
	State A (Space is Empty): If PIR input reads LOW, the PWM signal writes a duty cycle value of 0 (system overrides to an off state to save 100% of passive overheads). 
	State B (Space is Occupied): When PIR goes HIGH, the AI loop reads the current ADC value from the LDR. If daylight is abundant, the PWM duty cycle hovers low (1%" to " 20%). As natural light diminishes, the edge logic linearly scales the PWM value upward to 100% intensity, matching standard task constraints flawlessly. 
